@* THE DELIBERATE REFUSAL decision 162 DREW, and the one shape of a content region it will not emit.

   A <CascadingValue> emits NO element of its own, so at the template ROOT its content belongs to
   `target` -- and a region needs a container to lay its rows into. `target` is one, which is how a
   root @if compiles (decision 89), but decision 89 owns the WHOLE template: there is nothing else in
   it. Here the cascade has SIBLINGS. A region's rows are laid down with the BINDINGS, which run
   before the attach that inserts those siblings, so this source would render the rows FIRST, then
   #b, then #t -- the document silently rearranged.

   Refused rather than reordered. Wrapping the content in ONE element gives the region a container
   and compiles: that is exactly what baseline/ContentRegion.Blazor/App.razor writes, and the oracle
   measures its order against Blazor's (BENCH n°68).

   `items` IS reassigned by Add, so the @foreach itself is in subset (decision 140) -- this fixture
   refuses for the cascade and for nothing else. *@
<button id="b" @onclick="Add">b</button><CascadingValue Value="@level">@foreach (int n in items)
{
    <li @key="n">@n</li>
}</CascadingValue><p id="t">t</p>

@code {
    private int level = 1;
    private List<int> items = new List<int> { 1, 2, 3 };
    private List<int> _pool = new List<int> { 3, 4, 1, 5, 2 };

    void Add() { items = _pool.Where(x => x != 2).ToList(); }
}
